                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d718">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/3437</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-25T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4753. Your despatch No. 5901, March 7, 1917. Department believes that its
                    cablegram No. 4566. of 4 p.m., March 20, 1917, adequately covers all points
                    raised in Foreign Office note of March 5 transmitted with your despatch
                    concerning proposal for release of German and Austrian goods.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
